<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>FME - CHERNOBYL 1986 - 1996</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=000000 TEXT=FFFFFF>
 <FONT SIZE=-1><A HREF=chernidx.html>[Back to Index]</A> <A HREF=../csr/ukrain.html>[Country Status Report - Ukraine]</A> <A HREF=../contact.html>[How to contact For Mother Earth]</A> <A HREF=../webers.html>[About this Web.site]</A></FONT><BR><BR>
<CENTER>
 <B><FONT SIZE=8>Chernobyl</FONT><BR>
 <FONT SIZE=4>1986 - 1996</FONT><BR><BR></B>
 <IMG SRC=../images/zw_8696.gif><BR><BR>
 <IMG SRC=../images/left.gif><IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=80% SRC=../images/middle.gif><IMG SRC=../images/right.gif><BR>
</CENTER>


<PRE>
<H2>Walking to the Chernobyl 30-km zone</H2> 
<H3>A story you didn't read in the newspaper</H3>

Gent, May 2nd 1996 - With this article I wish to refrain from
repeating all the things you have heard on the radio, seen on TV, or
read in the newspaper the previous weeks concerning the tenth
anniversary of the Chernobyl disaster . It is a personal story and
some reflections. 

<B>*Kiev, April 17th</B>

Camera's were rolling and the rain was falling when
we arrived at the Chernobyl church in Kiev on Wednesday morning April
17th. Fifty locals and fifty walkers from all faiths and more than
10 different countries gathered.  They had white radiation-suits
and dust-masks, while carrying 83 signs with the crossed names of
evacuated villages and districts in the Ukraine.  Banners called
for the immediate closure of the Chernobyl NPP, and all nuclear
reactors worldwide. 
 
While waiting for the orthodox priest -who would come more than one
hour later-  I improvised a ceremony in the church. I explained the
meaning of the staff which we received last year from Skyhawk, a
Blackfoot North American Indian. Skyhawk made the staff last year,
and it was carried by walkers from Brussels to Moscow.  The staff
has the shell of a turtle representing Mother Earth, an Eagle
feather representing the sky and the creation, and four owl-feathers
representing the four directions, the four elements -water, fire, air
and water- and the four races.  The staff represents the unity and
connection of all - all being one. A staff has been used for ages by
messengers in American Indian communities when a messenger ran to
a different tribe or band. Skyhawk gave us the staff for protection,
as well as for the message we would bring from village to village,
town to town. The staff also helps me remind the suffering from
Indigenous People who have been affected as no others by nuclear
developments : uranium mining, nuclear testing, and now the
increasing storage of nuclear waste on their sacred homelands.

After the ceremony the group held a symbolic die-in, and
following the blessing from the orthodox priest the walkers left for
the railway station. A train took them aprox 160km (100 miles) west
of Kiev, to the city of Korostin.  In Korostin the people welcomed
the walkers with a meal. Jan and Caroline had a free evening, as they
were the wonderful cooks facilitating the mobile vegetarian kitchen.

<B>* April 18th - April 25th</B>

The next morning under a radiant sun and silent blue sky a meeting
with local politicans and doctors followed on the main square. They
welcomed the fifty walkers and talked about the disastrous
economical and medical consequences in their area. The message of
the walkers 'that the only nuclear power plant we need is the sun'
was received with enthusiasm by the nearly 500 locals who
had gathered there. It was amazing and re-empowering to notice that
the walkers were joined to Korostin's city limits by at least 200
people. It became clear to everyone that the walk would become a
powerful experience. 

And as we walked between 25 to 38 km/day to the villages or small
Ukrainian towns of Ignatpol, Ovruch, Narodichi, Marianovka,
Kraciatichi, Ivankov and finally Ditiatke, the same stories were
repeated, and every step we grew stronger. All those places are
inhabited settlements, but now contaminated post-Chernobyl wastelands
with dramatic human-stories. More than once, our hosts, often school
headmasters, would declare that they know of no healthy children in
their school. It was heartbreaking to meet these people in the midst
of this tragedy, as the autorities give almost no help at all, yes,
even close hospitals, and cut on medical personnel and equipment.
I felt so much despair when I looked in the eyes of those beautiful
innocent children. I know what to say when somebody will tell me
that nuclear power is cheap?? 

A special event was the walk from Narodichi to Paleskoye. Due to a
flooded road we couln't go according to our plan. Forest fires
blocked other alternatives. So we ended up receiving a special permit
to walk through six evacuated villages, and changed our campsite to
the school of Marianovka. It became a long walk of 38km. The sun was
burning, and the group went silent as we reached the radiation sign
announcing the evacuated area. No sounds of humans reached us as we
walked through the villages. Houses were looted, glass broken,
yellow-colored pictures remembered the previous inhabitants. Weeds
were taking over. Yes, in a way it was a beautiful area, an area
with the absence of men! But you couldn't forget 'why'. I will
never forget this one house, as a house from a fairy tale: a wooden
spotless white house, with sky blue windows. Two old women -mother
and daughter- clothed in rugs had returned to live in their home.
To the only place where they feel happy, close to the land they
have always lived and worked on, close to their ancestors which are
buried in the graveyard of the village. I will never forget those
people. 

<B>* Political and radio-active fall-out</B>

It seemed that all those beautiful people became not only the victim
of radio-active fall-out, but also of political and economical
mechanisms. They are also victims of a worldwide conspiracy of the
nuclear industry, the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), and
pro-nuclear governments who have been minimizing and still continue,
the effect of the Chernobyl disaster since April 26th 1986.

The Chernobyl accident had indeed enormous political and economical
consequences for the nuclear industry in the West.  Western
anti-nuclear activists suddenly received proof for their worst
predictions. What would never happen according to the nucleocrats
happened! As a result of Chernobyl, construction of NPPs was halted
in many countries, while orders for new ones were cancelled.
Belarus, Poland, Belgium, Italy, Germany, .... are some examples.
And today we learn that in Western Europe only France continues to
build new NPP's. Good news for the West, but bad news for Central
and Eastern Europe and the southern hemisphere.

<B>* The western nuclear industry moving East</B>

As vultures, the western nuclear industry moved their activities to
those places, and under the disguise of 'safety' they are now
upgrading Eastern NPP and building new Western 'safe' NPP.

-Ukraine-
Let's for example look at the agreement of the G7 and the European
Union on closing down Chernobyl by the year 2000. They promised 2.3
billion US$, 500 million in grants and 1.8 billion in loans. 1.3
billion US$ will be used to complete new nuclear power stations in
the Ukraine. 

-Belarus-
The Belarussian President visited the evacuated zone last week in
his country. He invited the relocated people to resettle in
the 'zone', as he declared this plutonium, cesium and strontium
sprinkled area to be safe. What is the role of the nuclear industry
in this? Well, in an article from the London based Uranium
Institute (an umbrella organisation from the nuclear industry) they
state that the biggest problem for nuclear energy in Belarus is the
'public opinion', who was affected as no other by Chernobyl.  To
this end a Scientific Training and Information Centre was opened in
Minsk in 1993 'to inform and educate the public about nuclear
power'. The Uranium Institute states that Belarus cannot manage
without nuclear power, and should have the first operating NPP by
the year 2005. 
 
More of those revolting examples. Westinghouse  (USA) is finishing
Temelin NPP in the Czech Republic, Siemens (Germany) and EDF (France)
are happy :-) to announce they'll be finishing the Mochovce NPP in
Slovakia, ....

<B>* Alarm!!</B>

During this walk it merged to every cell of my body:  I believe we
urgently need a solidarity movement with anti-nuke groups in those
countries where they are constructinyg NPP's, while on the other hand
Westerners need to expose the practices of the western nuclear
maffia and allied governments. FOR MOTHER EARTH also launched an
international petition demanding the reform of the UN IAEA -stop
promotion of nuclear power- and the creation of a new UN Energy
Agency to promote renewable energy. 

Yes, this is why we were walking, and our message was
welcomed. Hundreds of schoolchildren joined us in the morning
circle, and walked for some kilometers as we left their
school. In the evening people came to the cultural events the walk
musicians organised. They took the flyers, shook our hands, ... we
will never forget. And they gave us a lot of strenghth for the
final actions of the walk : a non-violent blockade of Chernobyl.

<B>April 26th</B>

Half past midnight forty walkers left the cultural centre for a 2 km
silent torch-light walk to the Ditiatke checkpoint. The night was
silent except for the frogs singing as we passed a large pond.  Fifty
meters from the barrier and the checkpoint we made a circle.

At exactly 01:23:40 a.m. we lighted emergency flares, and
the walkers made a die-in. After the die-in we made a large circle
and passed the staff. Everyone shared why they had come to the walk.
Among the walkers was a ten-year-old boy, Maksim Kuzin of Mogilev, a
contaminated area in Belarus.  Maksim wore a gas mask expressing his
protest at having to grow up under the shadow of Chernobyl. Other
participants included Oleg, a man who at the time of the accident
lived in Pripyat, 2 km from the plant, and Natasha Zamorskaya from
Zhitomir, Ukraine who joined the Walk because her father, a
Chernobyl-aftermath construction worker in 1986, died of cancer
three years ago. The circle was ended with two local women who shared
briefly their grief. They would be waiting the whole night at the
check-point to be allowed in the 'zone' as they were on their way
to the graveyard. One woman used to live in the city of Chernobyl,
the other in Pripyat. 
 
After the circle the road was blocked with a large banner calling
to shut down all nuclear power plants, and the 83 signs of evacuated
villages and regions of Ukraine, and a small fire was lit.  The
vigil lasted till 6 a.m.  At sunrise a tree was planted. There were
no arrests at this action. 

- Death-road tracks blocked -
A second action started at 01:23 a.m. on the raiway-tracks near the
city of Slavutich. Slavutich was specially built following the 1986
accident to replace the abandoned city of Pripyat that housed
Chernobyl plant workers. Today 40.000 people live in this new city
which was built in contaminated land. 

Eleven activists blocked the railway. Four people chained themselves
to the 'death-road tracks'. The railway is connecting Slavutich
directly with the Chernobyl NPP. Signs with the names of the most
dangerous nuclear reactors in various countries throughout the world
were planted near the tracks, while they were also holding a 15
meter banner calling to 'Stop nuclear terrorism'. 

At 4:45 a.m. police cut the locks the activists had used to secure
themselves to the tracks.  At 5:00 am the first morning train
carrying Chernobyl plant workers passed the site. The activists were
then taken to the police station for questioning.  They were
released at 11:30 a.m. after paying a fine of 150.000 koupon/person
(= O.75 US$) 

On Saturday April 27th the walk was offically closed with a
concert performed by various CIS bands that are calling themselves
"Musicians for Alternative Energy Sources".

The total of 50+ members of FOR MOTHER EARTH taking part in these
actions are from Belarus, Belgium, Denmark, Finland, Germany, the
Netherlands, Romania, Slovakia, the UK, Ukraine, and the USA.  This
walk was organised in partnership with the Ukrainian NGO 'Union of
Salvation of Chernobyls, a citizens network of
radiation-monitoring. 

<B>Other actions :</B>

Additional actions were carried out by FOR MOTYHER EARTH on April
26th. In Belgium twenty FOR MOTHER EARTH activists walked from the
city of Antwerp to the Doel NPP; in Slovakia FME and Greenpeace
activists did an action near the Bohunice NPP. In Amsterdam on
April 27th an alternative energy bike tour jointly organized by
Omslag and FME will culminate with a national "No More Chernobyls"
demonstration.  The cyclists began pushing their peddles from five
different nuclear facilities in the Netherlands.

FOR MOTHER EARTH demands the immediate closure of the Chernobyl NPP
and the global phase-out of nuclear energy.  FME also demands the
start of urgent programs for implementing energy efficiency and the
use of renewable energy sources (solar, wind, biomass).  For Mother
Earth believes we must stop nuclear pollution at its source - the
mining of uranium.

There are now FOR MOTHER EARTH groups in Belarus, Belgium, Finland,
Germany, Netherlands, Rumania, Slovakia, Ukraine and the USA. 

FOR MOTHER EARTH is a non-violent, international, non-profit
citizens organisation, which takes initiatives to promote
human rights, disarmament and protection of the environment
and all creatures, from the premise of an understanding that
the Earth is a creation to be honored and respected as our
Mother.

<B>What can you do:</B>

1. Become active in a anti-nuclear/pro-renewable energy group
2. Ask for our international petition
3. Order the 'No More Chernobyls Fingerbook', a guide to stop the
   Western nuclear industry's expansion in Eastern Europe
4. Support FOR MOTHER EARTH with a financial donation. Postal
   account for international postal cheques 000-1618561-19, 
   Gewad 15, B-9000 Gent 
5. Save energy and use renewable energy  
6. Contact us with your questions, suggestions, .... 

 -end-
 
</PRE>

