<H1>LAKA</H1>
<H2>National center for documentation and research
on nuclear energy & the resistance against it.</H2>

<PRE>
 The LAKA foundation is becoming more and more an important
 center for those who want information about nuclear energy and
 topics related to this phenomenon. The archive was established
 in 1982 by one of the founders, who used his cellar for the
 collection of all kind of material on nuclear energy. In 1988
 the archive became institutionalized as LAKA. 
</PRE>
<P>
<PRE>
 At LAKA, several dozen daily, weekly and monthly published
 papers from the Netherlands and foreign countries are clipped
 and systematically filed into a document archive. LAKA's
 collection of 100,000 clippings is the most important part of
 the document center. Further, we maintain files of magazines,
 a book collection, and an archive of films and video documentaries. 
</PRE>

<H3>THE ARCHIVE COVERS OVER 110 COUNTRIES AND IS CATEGORIZED BY
SUBJECTS INCLUDING THE FOLLOWING:</H3>

<PRE>
 Costs of nuclear energy, insurance/liability, accidents,
 uranium mining/stock/prices, enrichment, dismantling, reprocessing, 
 breeder reactors, risk analysis, source terms, evacuation plans in 
 case of a nuclear emergency, radiation, waste
 storage, transports, plutonium, proliferation, consequences of
 military attacks on nuclear installations, illegal trading,
 nuclear terrorism, IAEA, Euratom, ICRP, the nuclear industry
 and its lobbies, nuclear fusion, nuclear satellites, nuclear
 propulsion, depleted uranium (DU) in non-nuclear weapon systems
 and civilian use of DU, food irradiation, electrical
 utilities, history of the anti-nuclear movement, repression,
 nuclear energy and human rights.

 NEWSPAPER CUTTINGS:    from more than 25 national and interna-
                        tional newspapers. 100,000 cuttings di-
                        vided into 500 subjects.
 LIBRARY:               3000 books and brochures. A wide range
                        from technical literature to action
                        leaflets.
 MAGAZINES:             international magazines, partly from
                        the nuclear industry, partly from
                        environmental organisations.
 VIDEOS:                alternative productions, newsflashes, 
                        documentaries, etc. 
</PRE>
<P>
<PRE>
 Lists of books and video are available on request.
</PRE>

<H3>CAMPAIGNS AND PROJECTS</H3>

<PRE>
 In 1989 the LAKA foundation organized a succesful international
 congress for the European radical antinuclear movement. At
 that time we made contact with environmental groups in today's
 Czech Republic and Slovakia. This resulted in an extensive
 exchange of information. LAKA played a key role in offering
 tools to Czech and Slovak activists to help them inform citizens
 about the nuclear programs in their countries. 
</PRE>
<P>
<PRE>
 Current projects (1995) of LAKA are the contibutions to the
 Walk Across Europe by the international organisation For
 Mother Earth (FME) and a project on depleted uranium (DU)
 weapons.
</PRE>
<P>
<PRE>
 From January to October 1995 FME holds a 5000-kilometer
 walk from London to Moscow to demonstrate against nuclear
 energy, nuclear weapons, and especially the Non-Proliferation
 Treaty (NPT), which is due for extension in May 1995. The NPT,
 we believe, discriminates against the nuclear have-not nations
 while encouraging continuing proliferation by the superpowers.
 Further, the 'Atoms for Peace' concept is a fig-leaf for the
 progress towards full weapons capability in advanced nuclear
 powered nations like Japan. In order to have a nuclear-free
 world, we need a better NPT. The For Mother Earth country
 status reports, written by LAKA, provides all kinds of information
 about nuclear facilities in the countries that will
 host the march.
</PRE>
<P>
<PRE>
 The DU project began during spring 1992. Preparing for a visit
 to Iraq, a LAKA staffer discovered that the US-led Gulf coalition
 used DU antitank munitions and DU armoured vehicles for
 the first time on a battlefield scale. The severe medical and
 environmental impact of DU is well-known. DU is a very toxic
 waste, chemically as well as radiologically. 
</PRE>
<P>
<PRE>
 DU is also used for counterweights in aircraft design,
 leading to results after an air crash that are comparable to
 the impact of DU penetrators used in warfare. Such crashes of
 planes with DU took place, for example, in Amsterdam (Oct. 4,
 1992) and in Remscheid (FRG, April 1988).
</PRE>
<P>
<PRE>
 In co-operation with organisations and individuals involved
 in the DU-issue, we have set up a European DU-project. We have
 at our disposal a large amount of documentation on the current
 proliferation of DU weapons and are willing to serve as an
 information center in Europe on this issue.
</PRE>
<P>
<PRE>
 In order to guarantee our independence, LAKA has no structural
 income. We are totally dependent on the financial support of
 people who appreciate our work or use our resources. We respond
 to over 1,000 information requests per year, and most of 
 our work is offered free of charges to individuals or non-
 profit organizations. We sometimes charges fees to corporations,
 big institutions or journalists.
</PRE>


<B>LAKA  Foundation<BR>
Ketelhuisplein 43<BR>
NL-1054 RD  Amsterdam<BR>
phone/fax: +31 20 61 68 294<BR></B>
<P>
The LAKA foundation can also be contacted by E-mail:
<A HREF=mailto:laka@laka.aps.nl>laka@laka.aps.nl</A>. Our bank account is at Postbanknr.
5780452 in Ede, the Netherlands. The office is open during
working-days from 10 a.m. till 5 o'clock p.m. and on thursday
till 9 o'clock.

<HR>

 <ADRESS>
  &copy '95 LAKA Foundation - Web.site &copy For Mother Earth International, Gent, Belgium
 <ADRESS>
</FONT>

</BODY>
</HTML>
