<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Walk to Chernobyl</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>
<H1><IMG SRC=../images/walkcher.gif ALT="" BORDER=0>
 WALKING TO CHERNOBYL
</H1>
<H2>A story you didn't read in the newspaper 
by Pol D'Huyvetter)</H2>

<B><P>Gent (Belgium), May 2nd 1996</P></B> 
<P>- With this article I wish to refrain 
from repeating all the things you have heard on the radio, seen on TV, 
or read in the newspaper the previous weeks concerning the tenth 
anniversary of the Chernobyl disaster .It  is a personal story and some 
reflections.<P>

<B><P>Kiev, April 17thth</P></B>
<P>Camera's were rolling and the rain was falling when we arrived at the 
Chernobyl church in Kiev on Wednesday morning April 17thth. Fifty 
locals and fifty walkers from all faiths and more than 10 different 
countries gathered. They had white radiation-suits and dust-masks, 
while carrying 83 signs with the crossed names of evacuated villages 
and districts in the Ukraine. Banners called for the immediate closure 
of the Chernobyl NPP, and all nuclear reactors worldwide. While 
waiting for the orthodox priest who would come more than one hour 
later I improvised a ceremony in the church. I explained the meaning 
of the staff which we received last year from Skyhawk, a Blackfoot 
North American Indian. Skyhawk made the staff last year, and it was 
carried by walkers from Brussels to Moscow. The staff has the shell of 
a turtle representing Mother Earth, an Eagle feather representing the 
sky and the creation, and four owl-feathers representing the four 
directions, the four elements -water, fire, air and water- and the four 
races. The staff represents the unity and connection of all - all being 
one. A staff has been used for ages by messengers in American Indian 
communities when a messenger ran to a different tribe or band. 
Skyhawk gave us the staff for protection, as well as for the message we 
would bring from village to village, town to town. The staff also helps 
me remind the suffering from Indigenous People who have been 
affected as no others by nuclear developments : uranium mining, 
nuclear testing, and now the increasing storage of nuclear waste on 
their sacred homelands. After the ceremony the group held a symbolic 
die-in, and following the blessing from the orthodox priest the walkers 
left for the railway station. A train took them aprox 160km (100 
miles) west of Kiev, to the city of Korostin. In Korostin the people 
welcomed the walkers with a meal. Jan and Caroline had a free 
evening, as they were the wonderful cooks facilitating the mobile 
vegetarian kitchen.</P>

<B><P>April 18th - April 25th</P></B>
<P>The next morning under a radiant sun and silent blue sky a meeting 
with local politicans and doctors followed on themain square. They 
welcomed the fifty walkers and talked about the disastrous economical 
and medical consequences in their area. The message of the walkers 
`that the only nuclear power plant we need is the sun' was received 
with enthusiasm by the nearly 500 locals who had gathered there. It 
was amazing and re-empowering to notice that the walkers were 
joined to Korostin's city limits by at least 200 people. It became clear to 
everyone that the walk would become a powerful experience. And as 
we walked between 25 to 38 km/day to the villages or small 
Ukrainian towns of Ignatpol, Ovruch, Narodichi, Marianovka, 
Kraciatichi, Ivankov and finally Ditiatke, the same stories were 
repeated, and every step we grew stronger. All those places are 
inhabited settlements, but now contaminated post-Chernobyl 
wastelands with dramatic human-stories. More than once, our hosts, 
often school headmasters, would declare that they know of no healthy 
children in their school. It was heartbreaking to meet these people in 
the midst of this tragedy, as the autorities give almost no help at all, 
yes, even close hospitals, and cut on medical personnel and equipment. 
I felt so much despair when I looked in the eyes of those beautiful 
innocent children. I know what to say when somebody will tell me that 
nuclear power is cheap?? A special event was the walk from Narodichi 
to Paleskoye. Due to a flooded road we couln't go according to our 
plan. Forest fires blocked other alternatives. So we ended up receiving 
a special permit to walk through six evacuated villages, and changed 
our campsite to the school of Marianovka. It became a long walk of 
38km. The sun was burning, and the group went silent as we reached 
the radiation sign announcing the evacuated area. No sounds of 
humans reached us as we walked through the villages. Houses were 
looted, glass broken, yellow-colored pictures remembered the previous 
inhabitants. Weeds were taking over. Yes, in a way it was a beautiful 
area, an area with the absence of men! But you couldn't forget `why'. I 
will never forget this one house, as a house from a fairy tale: a wooden 
spotless white house, with sky blue windows. Two old women -mother 
and daughter- clothed in rugs had returned to live in their home. To 
the only place where they feel happy, close to the land they have 
always lived and worked on, close to their ancestors which are buried 
in the graveyard of the village. I will never forget those people.</P>

<P>Political and radio-active fall-out It seemed that all those
beautiful people became not only the victim of  radio-active
fall-out, but also of political and economical mechanisms.  They are
also victims of a worldwide conspiracy of the nuclear  industry, the
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), and pro- nuclear
governments who have been minimizing and still continue,  the effect
of the Chernobyl disaster since April 26thth 1986.  The Chernobyl
accident had indeed enormous political and economical  consequences
for the nuclear industry in the West. Western anti- nuclear activists
suddenly received proof for their worst predictions.  What would
never happen according to the nucleocrats happened! As  a result of
Chernobyl, construction of NPPs was halted in many  countries, while
orders for new ones were cancelled. Belarus, Poland,  Belgium, Italy,
Germany,.... are some examples. And today we learn  that in Western
Europe only France continues to build new NPP's.  Good news for the
West, but bad news for Central and Eastern Europe  and the southern
hemisphere.  THE WESTERN NUCLEAR INDUSTRY MOVING EAST
As vultures, the western nuclear industry moved their activities to 
those places, and under the disguise of `safety' they are now upgrading 
Eastern NPP and building new Western `safe' NPP.</P>

<P>UKRAINE</P>
<P>Let's for example look at the agreement of the G7 and the European 
Union on closing down Chernobyl by the year 2000.
They promised 2.3 billion US$, 500 million in grants and 1.8 billion in 
loans. 1.3 billion US$ will be used to complete new nuclear power 
stations in the Ukraine.</P>

<P>BELARUS</P>
<P>The Belarussian President visited the evacuated zone last week in his 
country. He invited the relocated people to resettle in the `zone', as he 
declared this plutonium, cesium and strontium sprinkled area to be 
safe. What is the role of the nuclear industry in this?
Well, in an article from the London based Uranium Institute (an 
umbrella organisation from the nuclear industry) they state that the 
biggest problem for nuclear energy in Belarus is the `public opinion', 
who was affected as no other by Chernobyl. To this end a Scientific 
Training and Information Centre was opened in Minsk in 1993 `to 
inform and educate the public about nuclear power'.
The Uranium Institute states that Belarus cannot manage without 
nuclear power, and should have the first operating NPP by the year 
2005.</P>

<P>MORE OF THOSE REVOLTING EXAMPLES.</P>
<P>Westinghouse (USA) is finishing Temelin NPP in the Czech Republic, 
Siemens (Germany) and EDF (France) are happy :-) to announce 
they'll be finishing the Mochovce NPP in Slovakia, ....  ALARM!!
During this walk it merged to every cell of my body: I believe we 
urgently need a solidarity movement with anti-nuke groups in those 
countries where they are constructinyg NPP's, while on the other hand 
Westerners need to expose the practices of the western nuclear maffia 
and allied governments. FOR MOTHER EARTH also launched an 
international petition demanding the reform of the UN IAEA -stop 
promotion of nuclear power- and the creation of a new UN Energy 
Agency to promote renewable energy. Yes, this is why we were 
walking, and our message was welcomed. Hundreds of schoolchildren 
joined us in the morning circle, and walked for some kilometers as we 
left their school. In the evening people came to the cultural events the 
walk musicians organised. They took the flyers, shook our hands, ...we 
will never forget. And they gave us a lot of strenghth for the final 
actions of the walk : a non-violent blockade of Chernobyl.</P>

<B><P>April 26th<P></B>
<P>Half past midnight forty walkers left the cultural centre
for a 2 km  silent torch-light walk to the Ditiatke checkpoint. The
night was silent  except for the frogs singing as we passed a large
pond. Fifty meters  from the barrier and the checkpoint we made a
circle. At exactly  01:23:40 a.m. we lighted emergency flares, and
the walkers made a  die-in. After the die-in we made a large circle
and passed the staff.  Everyone shared why they
had come to the walk. Among the walkers was a ten-year-old boy, 
Maksim Kuzin of Mogilev, a contaminated area in Belarus.Maksim 
wore a gas mask expressing his protest at having to grow up under the 
shadow of Chernobyl. Other participants included Oleg, a man who at 
the time of the accident lived in Pripyat, 2 km from the plant, and 
Natasha Zamorskaya from Zhitomir, Ukraine who joined the Walk 
because her father, a Chernobyl-aftermath onstruction worker in 
1986, died of cancer three years ago. The circle was joined with two 
local women who shared riefly their grief. They would be waiting the 
whole night at the heck-point to be allowed in the `zone' s they were 
on their way to the raveyard. One woman used to live in the city of 
Chernobyl, the other in Pripyat. After the circle the road was blocked 
with a large banner calling to shut down all nuclear power plants, and 
the 83 signs of evacuated villages and regions of Ukraine, and a small 
fire was lit, which a policeman ordered us to put it out immediately. 
But comparing our small fire with the one of ten years ago, he relaxed 
...and started telling his story. On April 27thth 1986 he was called to 
regulate traffic 300 meters from the burning reactor 4 (without any 
protection mask). Today he has serious health problems. He welcomed 
our action `but it comes too late'. The vigil lasted till 6 a.m. At sunrise a 
tree was planted. There were no arrests at this action.</P>

<P>Death-road tracks blocked</P>
<P>A second action started at 01:23 a.m. on the raiway-tracks near the 
city of Slavutich. Slavutich was specially built following the 1986 
accident to replace the abandoned city of Pripyat that housed 
Chernobyl plant workers. Today 40.000 people live in this new city 
which was built in contaminated land. Eleven activists blocked the 
railway. Four people chained themselves to the `death-road tracks'. 
The railway is connecting Slavutich directly with the Chernobyl NPP. 
Signs with the names of the most dangerous nuclear reactors in 
various countries throughout the world were planted near the tracks, 
while they were also holding a 15 meter banner calling to `Stop 
nuclear terrorism'. At 4:45 a.m. police cut the locks the activists had 
used to secure themselves to the tracks. At 5:00 am the first morning 
train carrying Chernobyl plant workers passed the site. The activists 
were then taken to the police station for questioning. They were 
released at 11:30 a.m. after paying a fine of 150.000 koupon/person 
(= O.75 US$)<P>

<B><P>On Saturday April 27th</P></B>
<P>The walk was offically closed with a concert 
performed by various CIS bands that are calling themselves 
"Musicians for Alternative Energy Sources". 
The total of 50+ members of FOR MOTHER EARTH taking part in 
these actions are from Belarus, Belgium, Denmark, Finland, Germany, 
the Netherlands, Romania, Slovakia, the UK, Ukraine, and the USA.
This walk was organised in partnership with the Ukrainian NGO 
`Union of Salvation of Chernobyls, a citizens network of radiation-
monitoring.</P>

<H2>Other actions :</H2>

<P>On April 26thth in Belgium twenty FOR MOTHER EARTH activists 
walked from the city of Antwerp to the Doel NPP; in Slovakia FME and 
Greenpeace activists did an action near the Bohunice NPP. In 
Amsterdam on April 27thth an alternative energy bike tour jointly 
organized by Omslag and FME will culminate with a national "No 
MoreChernobyls" demonstration. The cyclists began pushing their 
peddles from five different nuclear facilities in the Netherlands.
FOR MOTHER EARTH demands the immediate closure of the Chernobyl NPP
and the  global phase-out of nuclear energy.  FME also demands the
start of urgent programs for implementing  energy efficiency and the
use of renewable energy sources (solar,  wind, biomass).
For Mother Earth believes we must stop nuclear pollution at its source 
- the mining of uranium.</P>

<P>What can you do:</P>
<UL>
<P>1. Become active in an anti-nuclear/pro-renewable energy group</P>
<P>2. Ask for our international petition</P>
<P>3. Order the `No More ChernobylsFingerbook',
   a guide to stop the Western nuclear industry's expansion
   in Eastern Europe</P>
<P>4. Support FOR MOTHER EARTH with a financial donation. 
   Postal account for international postal cheques 000-1618561-19,
   Gewad 15, B-9000 Gent, Belgium</P>
<P>5. Save energy and use renewable energy</P> 
<P>6. Contact us with your questions, suggestions, ....</P> 
</UL>

<A HREF=../index.html><IMG SRC="../images/home.gif" BORDER=0 ALT="Back to Homepage"></A>
