<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Indignenous Peoples Uranium Speaking tour in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>

<H1>
 <IMG SRC=../images/walkura.gif ALT="" BORDER=0>
 Indigenous Peoples Uranium Speaking tour in Europe - fall 1997
</H1>

<I>Birds in the sky - Fish in the water - Uranium in the Ground</I>

<P>Gent, August 30 1996 - In autumn 1997 several Indigenous Peoples
representatives will start a speaking tour in Europe. FOR MOTHER EARTH
plans to invite Indigenous Peoples' representatives from several
continents to share their experience with uranium mining companies
destroying their lives and land to meet the demands for nuclear fuel in
industrialized nations. </P>

<PWith this speaking tour FOR MOTHER EARTH wants to inform the public
about the first step in the nuclear chain - and the negative consequences
for people and the environment.</P>

<P>An example. Belgium has seven nuclear reactors, which consume about 110
tons of enriched uranium a year (aprox. 1.000 tons of natural uranium). As
Belgium has no uranium reserves on its territory, all uranium is imported.
According to Patrick De Vos, a spokesperson of ELectrabel (the main
electricity company), today's uranium needs of the company are met by
imports from Australia, Canada, China, CIS, France, Gabon, Namibia, Niger,
South-Africa and the USA.</P>

<P>And we know that in several cases mining companies are violating
landrights of Indigenous People. </P>

<P>Nuclear testing programs have learned us that the nuclear industry, and
its economical, financial, military and political allies, have shown no
concerns about sacrifying the sacred lands of Indigenous People for their
nuclear experiments (i.e. Maohi, Western Shoshone Indians, Australian
Aboriginals, Kazahk, Nenets, ...)</P>

<P>We see this pattern repeated with the enormous problems of rad-waste
storage. Nobody wants nuclear waste in the back-yard. In Canada and the
USA more and more 'Indian reservations' become prime targets to get rid of
this burning problem. </P>

<P>FOR MOTHER EARTH wants to continue to support Indigenous Peoples struggle
for self-determination, expose and oppose the racist policies of the
nuclear industry. </P>

<P>With this tour FOR MOTHER EARTH wants to inform and encourage citizens
groups to demand a halt of nuclear contamination and colonialism at its
source : the mining of uranium. With this European tour we want to create
new links and strenghten a anti-uranium mining network. </P>

<P>The tour will start in autumn 1997 in Belgium. - starting i.e.  on October
12th -the International Day of Solidarity with Indigenous Peoples. </P>

<P>FME members in Belarus, Belgium, Finland, Germany, Netherlands, Rumania,
Slovakia and Ukraine are interested to organise events in their country.
To make this tour succesful we want and need to cooperate with other
NGO's. If you are interested, if you have info, please contact us today.</P>

<H2>HELP NEEDED</H2>

<P>As a frist step we have created a working group in Belgium. But to make
this tour happen we want to cooperate with other gropus and people, and
need support.</P>

<P>Now we are looking for : </P>

<UL>
 <LI> People who want to be part of writing a brochure to be publicized in
   september 1997.
 <LI> European NGO's and individuals who want to help organise events in
   their country. We envision press-events, public gatherings,
   non-violent (direct) actions, meetings with politicians, ...
 <LI> Finances:
 <UL> 
  <LI>Financial contributions  are welcomed on FME postal account :
   000-1618561-19 FOR MOTHER EARTH. Gewad 15, 9000 Gent, Belgium
  <LI>Also suggestions for sponsors (i.e. foundations, individuals,
   ...) are needed today!
 </UL>
</UL>

<B><P>Contact</P></B>
Pol D'Huyvetter, For Mother Earth International 
<BR>E-mail: <A HREF=mailto:int@fme.knooppunt.be>int@fme.knooppunt.be</A><B></P>

