<HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Indignenous Peoples Uranium Speaking tour in Europe</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY>

<H1>
 <IMG SRC=../images/walkura.gif ALT="" BORDER=0>
 Indigenous Peoples Uranium Speaking tour in Europe - fall 1997
</H1>

<H2>Uranium Book Project</H2>

<UL>
 <LI><A HREF="#history">History?</A> 
 <LI><A HREF="#motivation">Motivation</A>
 <LI><A HREF="#content">Content of book</A> 
 <LI><A HREF="#what">What you can do?</A>
</UL>

<A NAME="history">
<H3>History</H3>

<P>With the publication of a book we wish to deepen the work
which has been done by the organisers of the World Uranium Hearing
(WUH).</P>

<P>The WUH took place in Salzburg (Austria) in September 1992, and it
provided a forum to Indigenous Peoples from around the world to
testify about nuclear activities on their ancestral territories. </P>

<P>We were not able to attend the WUH, as our group was at that time
nearing the Nevada Test Site, the end of a 5.500km 'Walk across
America for Mother Earth'. A walk in solidarity with Native
Americans, especially with the Western Shoshone Indigenous People,
on whose land the USA and the UK exploded more then 800 nuclear
weapons. </P>

<P>And as the years slipped further, and new actions were
developed for a Treaty to halt nuclear testing, some of us continued
to wonder about the worldmap which was publicized by the WUH.</P>

<H4>It titles</H4>
 
<P>THE ONES NOBODY TALKS ABOUT</P>
<P>Victims of Uranium Mining and Atomic Tests</P>

<P>The map represents exclusively Indigenous Peoples affected by
nuclear colonialism.</P>
 
<H4>In Africa</H4>

<P>Sahraouis, Touareg, Peul, Nuba, Songhai, Hausa, Djerma, Eritreans,
Adja, Ewe, Fon, Bapounon, Bambuti, Pangwe, Myene, Ovambo, Ndebele,
Herero, Venda, Damara, San, Swazi, Nama, Tswana, Khoikhoi, Sotho,
Zulu and Xhosa </P>

<H4>In Asia</H4>

<P>Nenets, Dolgans, Evenks, CHukchee, Khakass, Buryats, Kazeakhs,
Tuvinbs, Khirgiz, Uigurs, Santal and Yami</P>

<H4>In Australia</H4>

<P>Gagudju, Martujarra, Kungarakan, Yaknunyara, Pinjantjat Jara and
Kokotha </P>

<H4>In the Pacific</H4>

<P>Marshall-Islanders, Kiritimati Kiribati, Maohi and Native Hawaians</P>

<H4>In North America</H4>

<P>Aleuts, Inuit, Dene, Cree, Spokane, Kootenay, Anishinabe, Yakima,
Lakota, Paiute, Navajo, Zuni, Western Shoshone, Hopi, Acoma,
Havasupai and Laguna Peublo </P>

<H4>In South America</H4>

<P>Yanomami, Shuar, Txukaramai, Kayapo, Quechua, Guarani and Tuhuelche</P>

<P>For us it continues to be a mind-blowing map, which does even claim
not to be complete. <P>

<P>Please don't hesitate to share and/or info you have!!</P>

<P>Yes, many questions raised when we looked to this map. Who are those
people? What has happened exactly? Are they affected by nuclear
testing or uranium ming? Or both? How has it affected their lives?
What is their struggle? Why don't we know? Where has the uranium been
coming from for the Belgian nuclear power plants? etc etc ...</P>

<P>During the past years we had hoped to come across a publication which
would give us answers. But we didn't find any which gave us the
complete picture. </P>

<P>We had to conclude that such a thing doesn't exist yet ... and
if we want it, we will have to make it ourselves.</P>

<P>And with the end of our campaign to end nuclear testing ... we wish
today to invest our resources and energy to explore and expose the
issue of uranium mining. </P>

<A NAME="motivation">
<H3>Motivation</H3>

<P>We believe that the global anti-nuclear movement has
neglected the issue of nuclear colonialism for too long.  With this
uranium project we wish to continue our efforts to explore and
expose the information of Indigenous Peoples struggle against the
nuclear industry and allied governments. And our experience
considering the evolution within the global coalition to stop nuclear
testing was hopeful. Many groups, individuals and politicians seemed
to take the issue of human-rights seriously, once they received the
information. </P>

<P>With the publication of hard facts on uranium mining vs. Indigenous
Peoples, we wish to create an extra opportunity for new alliances
between the anti-nuclear movement, pro-renewable energy groups,
Indigenous Peoples, and Indigenous Peoples Support Groups. The book
should be an extra tool in our struggle for self-determination for
Indigenous people and a nuclear free world. </P>

<A NAME="content">
<H3>Content of book</H3>

<H4>INTRODUCTION</H4>

<P>An introduction should give the reader insight on uranium mining,
its place in the nuclear cycle, the effects on environment and
health, and give intro on the global uranium market (supply and
demand). </P>

<H4>REGIONS</H4>

<P>In seperate chapters, we wish to have a closer look to
uranium mining on different continents.</P>

<P>We envision a general introduction for every region, summing up the
history of uranium mining and the policy towards Indigenous Peoples.
This introduction should also give the reader an overview of the
most important mining companies. </P>

<P>Further in these chapters we wish to go more in detail. The aim is
to gather concrete facts where uranium mining activities violate the
landrights of Indigenous People (past, present and future). We hope
to give information of the different mines (closed, open and
proposed) : location (with map), Indigenous Peoples (history,
present situation, statements on u-mining on their territory),
company, reserves, mining history, uranium contracts, environmental
and health impact, struggle and contacts. </P>

<H4>CONCLUSION</H4>

<P>And we are sure that this project should lead us to conclusions ...
especially the steps to take from here.</P>

<H4>APPENDIX</H4>

<P>In the appendix we should find data on the global uranium market
(supply and demand), contacts, ...</P>

<A NAME="what">
<H3>What can you do??</H3>

<UL>
 <LI> Give feed-back on this proposal as a first step

 <LI> Coordinate the research for Africa, Australia, Asia, Europe,
North America, Pacific and South America.

 <LI> People who are working locally and want to send their info to
regional coordinators

 <LI> Overall project coordinators, who want to be part of the
facilitating the overall project. At this time we are two people
here in Gent (Belgium) who are willing to do this.
This is Eric Gryp (retired Senator of Green Party) and myself.

<LI>People who wanna help to get a publisher interested

<LI>People who can look for funding

<LI>people who can help for distribution
 
</UL>

<P>Please feel invited to contribute, or make suggestions!!</P>

<B><P>Contact</P></B>
Pol D'Huyvetter, For Mother Earth International 
<BR>E-mail: <A HREF=mailto:int@fme.knooppunt.be>int@fme.knooppunt.be</A><B></P>

