<HTML>
<HEAD>
 <TITLE>Nuclear Weapons / Abolition 2000</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<H2><IMG SRC=../images/abolit.gif ALT="" HEIGHT=50 WIDHT=50 BORDER=0> Abolition 2000</H2>
<H3>Belgian peace activists win trial (pressrelease)</H3> 

<P><B>Court incompentent</B></P>

<P>Gent, October 1st 1996 - Two peace activists, Bernard De Witte and
Pol D'Huyvetter, had to appear on the 12th and 16th of September
before the Belgian police court in Beringen. The activists were part
of a group of six which climbed the barbed-wire fences of the
nuclear weapon base of Kleine Brogel on Decmeber 3th 1995. The
activists deployed a large banner calling 'nuclear weapons illegal'
near the bunkers containing a secret number of US B-61 nuclear
weapons.</P>

<P>For Mother Earth activist, Pol D'Huyvetter, stated in his defence
that the action was aimed to expose the illegality of nuclear
weapons on the Belgian military base. He said: 'today I feel
especially strenghtened by the verdict of the International Court of
Justice from La Hague, as they stated last July 8th that the threat
and use of nuclear weapons is contrary to international law in nearly
all situations'. Judge Leon Truyers clearly expressed his sympathy
with this by saying : 'This is a point of view which one can
indeed defend'. </P>

<P>The lawyers Johan Verstraeten and Frans Smeets pleaded the
incompetency of the policecourt. As this case is political, it
should be dealt with by a higher court with a jury. The judges'
verdicts issued on the 26th and 30th of September followed the
defence, and declared the court's incompentence. It is not clear
what the Public Prosecution will decide after this verdict. </P>

<P>The trial received attention on national radio, regional tevee and
several newspapers carried the story.</P>

<P>Activists from For Mother Earth (Belgium) and War Resistors
International (Flanders) are determined to continue civil
defence for the abolition of nuclear weapons. They believe this is
also an efficient way to publicize the ICJ ruling more widely.
They made a proposal for an international day of non-violent direct
actions at nuclear weapon labs and -bases on Nagasaki Day
next year - Saturday August 9th. </P>

<P>Note: Photo of action for publication is available on request</P>

