<html><HEAD><TITLE> Walk action report 5</TITLE></HEAD>

<body>
<A HREF="/~fme/wae/waeidx.html"><IMG SRC  = "/~fme/images/walkhome.gif" ALT="Walk Across Europe Home Page"></A>

<H2>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE</H2>
<H2>Caen (France) - Februari 8th 1995</H2>


<HR>
<H1>ANTI-NUKE MARCHERS HEADING TO PLUTONIUM FACTORIES OF LA HAGUE</H1>

<I>-> Photographs available on request !</I>

<P>
<B>Last January 12th one hundred fifty people marked the start of
the 5.500km Walk across Europe for a Nuclear-Free World at the
HQ of the European Union in Brussels. About fourty long-time
walkers plan to arrive at the Kremlin in Moscow on October
12th, the International Day of Solidarity with Indigenous
People.
</B><P>
The walk is organised by FOR MOTHER EARTH (FME), an internati-
onal non-violent grass-roots organisation. FME organised a
similar and succesful campaign from New York City to the
Nevada Nuclear Test Site in 1992.
<P>
So far an average of sixty people joined their feet. They had
actions at the military  headquarters of NATO (SHAPE) in Mons
(Belgium) and the French Operational Centre of Strategic
Airforces in Taverny and Evreux (COFAS 1 and 3). The walkers
have been welcomed by many local autorities and a delegation
was received at the French Presidential Palace l'Elysie in
Paris.
<P>
The walkers demand a Ban on Nuclear Testing and a Convention
to Ban Nuclear Weapons. They ask a review and extension of the
Non-Proliferation Treaty which will be discussed next April in
New York. They demand the complete Phase Out of Nucleur Power,
and they put the development of sustainable energy programs
forward.
<P>
FOR MOTHER EARTH also wants to raise awareness around the fate
of Indigenous People who are affected by uranium mining,
nuclear testing, and rad-waste storing on their homelands.
France has tested its bombs on lands of the Tuareg and Polyne-
sians. The French mining company COGEMA extracts uranium from
homelands of i.e. the Cree, Inuit, Tuareg and Peul People.
<P>
The walk is accompanied by a Danish truck with a 50m} mobile
exhibition on Susainable Energies coordinated by SNORE.
The Dutch collective Rampenplan provides organic vegetarian
food three times a day. A bus carries the gear, food and medi-
cal supplies. Local organizers in Belgium and France arranged
indoor campsites and detailed route sheets, organic food-
donations, debates, media-coverage and parties.
<P>
Walkers from Austria, Belgium, the Indian Blackfoot Nation,
Britain, Bulgaria, Canada, Denmark, France, The Netherlands,
Rumania, Sri Lanka, Switzerland, Ukraine, and the USA are now
on their way to the Plutonium factories of La Haque in France,
where they plan to have non-violent direct actions mid-februa-
ry.
<P>
They will cross the channel on their way to London. They'll be
back on the continent in March where larger actions are expec-
ted at the Nuclear Power Plant of Doel (Belgium) and Dodewaard
(Netherlands). In spring the walk will be in Germany, the
Czech Republic, Austria and Slovakia.
Ukraine and Belarus will be crossed this summer, where they
will commemorate the 50th anniversary of Hiroshima near the
NNP of Chernobyl on August 6th.
<P>
<HR>
For more information, registrations and financial support:

<address>
FOR MOTHER EARTH International, Gent, Belgium
</address><A HREF=/~fme/wae/waeidx.html>[INDEX]</A> <A HREF=wrep006.html>[NEXT]</A>
</body></htmll>




