<HEAD><TITLE>Walk action report 7 - La Hague  </TITLE></HEAD>

<body>
<A HREF="/~fme/wae/waeidx.html"><IMG SRC  = "/~fme/images/walkhome.gif" ALT="Walk Across Europe Home Page"></A>

<H2>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE</H2>
<H2>Released to mass-media on Feb. 15th  </H2>


<HR>
<H1>BLOCKADE OF PLUTONIUM FACTORIES AT LA HAGUE<BR>
Walkers denounce environmental racism of COGEMA
 </H1>

<P>
<B>This morning at 10 am, February 15th, 50 participants of the
5.500km walk from Brussels to Moscow started an action day at the
reprocessing plant of La Hague (France). The Cogema plutonium
plant, which is 20km from Cherbourg. At 10.30 they locked a first
gate by using a cryptonite U-lock. This gate was still locked at
4pm. Then, they all walked to the main gate where they had an
Indian ceremony and a die-in.  5 activists climbed over the main
gate and chained themselves to the gate to stop workers coming
through. Because of two gates locked a traffic jam was created
on the main road.As so far no violence has been used by police
and no one has been injured.
</B><P>

The other FOR MOTHER EARTH activists did a die-in in front of the
enterance, followed by an indian ceremony led by Skyhawk from the
North American Blackfeet Nation, to commemorate his grandfather
who was a victim of uraniummining going on on their sacred land.
On banners of the activists you could read some of their demands
for a nuclear-free world : an immediate halt of uranium mining
and plutonium production by the French company Cogema.
After a long negotiation, the activists unlocked themselves at
2.30 pm after a meeting was agreed with Mr. H. Acard, chief of
COGEMA's communications department. They handed Mr. H.Acard
several signs with the names of Indigenous people which are
affected by COGEMA. After the meeting, the actiists left the main
gate at 2.45 pm. There were no arrests or incidents.

<H3>Fish in the water, birds in the sky, uranium in the ground</H3>
<P>
The activists carried over sixty signs with the names of
Indigenous People who are affected by uranium mining.
Cogema is one of the leading suppliers of uranium concentrate in
the world with 20 to 28%. Cogema has uranium mining activities
in Europe (France, Spain and Sweden), the Americas (Canada, USA
and Ecuador), Australia and Africa (Niger and Gabon). According
to FOR MOTHER EARTH it are especially Indigenous People who
suffer from Cogema's mining activities.  The environmental group
named the Cree and Inuit American Indians, the Touareg and Peul
in Africa and for Australia the Aboriginals.
<P>
Pol D'Huyvetter, spokesperson FOR MOTHER EARTH said that "By
moving nuclear activities to Indigenous People's land, the
nuclear lobby proves that their activity is unsafe. Seventy to
eighty percent of all uranium mining worldwide takes place on
these people's lands. All nuclear testing programs did too." FOR
MOTHER EARTH has been campaigning since its beginning in 1991
against this environmental racism. "If it is as safe as they tell
us all the time, why didn't they test their atomic bombs in
France instead of Polynesia? Or why are the Canadian and US
governments spotting thirty Indigenous Nations to dump their
radioactive-waste?" wonders Pol D'Huyvetter. He continued by
stating that "The result of uranium mining has proven to be
disastrous. Around mining areas there is a significant raise of
cancer for the miners and people living in the area of mines. It
is time people get informed about this issue. We need to realize
that many people pay with their health and lifes and the
environmental destruction for our so-called clean nuclear
electricity, wether it is generated with uranium or with
plutonium.

<H3>Cogema leading the plutonium market</H3>
<P>
Cogema takes the leading role of reprocessing spent fuel on the
world (80 to 90%). Cogema reprocesses spent fuel from Belgium,
France, Germany, Japan, the Netherlands and Switzerland. It is
estimated that Cogema has already reprocessed 40.000 kg. of
plutonium. Five kilogram is enough for the production of a
nuclear bomb with the power of the one dropped on Nagasaki fifty
years ago. La Hague which was initially built for the French
military nuclear program, now tries to survive with a civilian
fast-breeder and MOX programs.
<P>
FOR MOTHER EARTH demands that the upcoming UN conference on the
NPT (Non-Proliferation Treaty) in New York negotiates a
Convention to halt reprocessing immediately.
The production of plutonium increases the risk of proliferation
and military use of plutonium. With a half-life of 24,000 years
for plutonium 239, and unpredictable political changes on this
time-frame, FOR MOTHER EARTH believes that Cogema's reprocessing
activity is a short-sighted irresponsable and criminal act
against the future unborn generations. The environmental
organization further states that all to this day produced
plutonium should be treated as waste. They also stressed that the
group Cogema has to carry this financial responsability for the
thousands of years to come.
<P>
Foreign walk participants from Belgium, the Netherlands, and
Switzerland in particular denounce the reprocessing of spent
nuclear fuel in La Hague coming from their country. They pledged
to do everything they can once they are back home to stop this
transport of nuclear waste to La Hague. They stated that France
may not become the nuclear dumpsite for their governments nuclear
energy policy. If they want nuclear power, they also have to take
the waste.
<P>
Sixty walkers from thirteen different countries left Brussels
last January 12th and arrived in Cherbourg yesterday. They will
leave CHerbourg Friday for Portsmouth (England). They plan to
commemorate the 50th anniversary of the bombing of Hiroshima in
Tjernobyl. They wish to reach the Kremlin on the 12th of October
1995, the International Day of Solidarity with Indigenous People.

<P>
<HR>
For more information, registrations and financial support:

<address>

FOR MOTHER EARTH International, Gent, Belgium

</address><A HREF=/~fme/wae/waeidx.html>[INDEX]</A> <A HREF=wrep008.html>[NEXT]</A>

</body>
</html>


