<HEAD><TITLE>Walk action report 16 - follow-up Japan </title></head>

<body>
<A HREF="/~fme/wae/waeidx.html"><IMG SRC="/~fme/images/walkhome.gif" ALT="Walk Across Europe Home Page"></A> <A HREF="/~walk/contacta.html"><IMG SRC  = "/~walk/images/contacta.gif" ALT="Contact Addresses"></A> <A HREF=wrep015.html><IMG SRC = "arrwleft.gif"></A><A HREF="wrepovv.html"><IMG SRC  = "actreprt.gif"  ALT="Action Report" ></A><A HREF=wrep017.html><IMG SRC = "arrwriht.gif"></A>

<H2>for immediate release</H2>
<H2>Cherbourg, Thursday February 23th 1995</h2>

<HR>
<b>This is a follow-up story which the mass-media, nor
Greenpeace Communications covered.</b>

<h1>FOR MOTHER EARTH joined Greenpeace in actions against rad-waste/top priority shipment from La Hague to Japan </h1>

<i>It is the story from Jonathan Castle sent to us by
mail. Jonathan Castle, previous captain of several
Greenpeace boats, offered his old sailing-boat to
FOR MOTHER EARTH activists to protest the shipment of rad-
waste/top-priority shipment to Japan.
Jonathan asked us to spread this story.
<br>
It covers his side of the story in Cherbourg, where 19
activist were arrested. Twelve from Greenpeace, seven from
FOR MOTHER EARTH.</i>
<p>
Hello, I'm Jonathan Castle, I come from Guernsey, a small
Island about 20 miles off the coast of Cap de la Hague, where
COGEMA have their vast nuclear reprocessing plant. One of the
two in the world, along with Sellafield in England. Even in
terms of nuclear power, reprocessing of spent fuel is
illogical. The plutonium produced is not needed or wanted
anymore, all that occurs is that the volume of irradiated
waste is increased a hundred fold, and more radioactivity is
discharged to the environment.
<p>
In the Channel Islands we have measurable amounts of radio-
activity in the beach seaweed. Seaweed that the few good
organic growers use on their land, so as usual, the innocent
suffer first, just like the Native and traditional People on
whose land uranium is mined.
<p>
I used to work for Greenpeace, from 1978 and the beginning of
the "Rainbow Warrior" days until 1990. As Greenpeace gradually
became more institutionalized and lost its spiritual
connection with the Earth, I could not feel as passionately
identified as I had - it was turning into just a job, and one
I wasn't proud of anymore.
<p>
The last few years, while I had seethed and pondered on the
increasing planetery threats, I hadn't done a lot. We had a
conference on nuclear transport in early February, I met old
friends, I thought, come on I better do something. So I came
up to Cherbourg in my boat, an old wooden sailing boat which
was originally a Breton fishing boat. I met the Greenpeace
people, locals who I knew from previous actions, and the "Moby
Dick" crew. It seemed for sure that Greenpeace would severely
restrict their own actions of protest due to a long standing
legal injunction in the UK by BNFL against them. Added to that
BNFL brought court proceedings in Cherbourg to keep Greenpeace
away. As part of the international nuclear conspiracy legal
systems regularly are used to support commerce, to protect the
big criminals. They don't represent justice but only order,
and a certain order which suits this establishment of the
time.
<p>
It seemed to me the "Moby Dick" would not be allowed -by
Greenpeace bosses- to take action, even though the young crew
was full of spirit and enthusiasm. They felt rejected and I
felt for them. By the way, I used to be Captain of that boat
for 3 years, doing many actions against nuclear transport
among other things. So I had to do something, on my own it
seemed.

<h2>Monday, Feb. 20th 1995</h2>

While hanging around the court house one day, where the BNFL-
PNFL/Greenpeace case was being heard, I couldn't help noticing
the FOR MOTHER EARTH people. They were very noticable! Drums,
radiation suits, colour, large banners with messages from the
heart, not the intellect : "Birds in the sky - fish in the
water - uranium in the ground". This gaunt faced long-hair
with an eye like the ancient Mayans, a Red Indian man,
dignified and calm, young enthusiastic people in costumes,
with smiles. Sort of like Greenpeace used to be! I liked the
look of them. Also their group had actually climbed the
nuclear loading crane and blocked the gates of COGEMA. So they
could act, on top of having convictions. First come the
convictions, the right spirit, but second must come some
practicality, the ability to get it together.

<h2>Tuesday, Feb. 21st</h2>
I am rather shy, but I made an approach to first SkyHawk, then
Pol. I would do something on my own or with Annie a friend of
the Earth from Guernsey, but better not to be alone, if
possible.

<h2>Wednesday, Feb. 22nd</h2>
They came, saw the boat, we had a common cause. On the
Wednesday afternoon we went in the boat "Les Deux Amis" over
to the area of the harbor in front of the loading crane. There
were about eight of the FOR MOTHER EARTH group, myself and
Annie, and two film crew from French TV. We had a fine
ceremony, laying a weath in the water for "The victims of the
Nuclear Industry 1945 - 1995". I found that extremely
worthwhile, a period of silence, contemplation, while
witnessing for these crimes against common people. A little
hassle from some police when we strayed towards the crane too
closely. A peaceful action, but one with power.
<p>
That evening I heard the "Pacific Pintail", the ship to carry
the cargo, was expected at an early time in the morning, so we
should be on guard all night. Now we were eight FOR MOTHER
EARTH - but eight who felt together, comfortable with each
other. Trust had built up sufficiently in this short time.
We would have a team of 4 on the boat, 4 on the land. On the
boat would be myself, Joey and Shygua from the Netherlands and
SkyHawk, representing himself but also the first victims of
the nuclear industry, the Native People from North America. I
felt honored to have these companions. I had also heard the
"Moby Dick" would finally be allowed to go into action. I was
so glad, well that was my old team, and I knew how happy the
crew would be. So the night's vigil began, after a good meal
together.

<h2>Thursday, Feb. 23th</h2>
Just sitting in the dark, waiting, rather cold, listening to
the port radio, drinking coffee, watching the Moby Dick for
movement. It came at 03.10 local time - an announcement over
the radio that a "priority ship" was entering the harbor, and
all other traffic was restricted. Well that had to be the one.
The Moby Dick got under way. Not one of the Greepeace's fleet
of too big, too expensive, too sophisticated ships, but the
little old beaten up reliable seaworthy wave little trawler.
Great! Greenpeace finding some remnants of its old soul, the
old warriors of the Rainbow spirit. I moved off right behind,
crossing the harbor, half a mile to the loading berth. Weather
had improved, dark sky, wind down to a good breeze, for a
change. The Pacific Pintail's lights were visible, just
approaching the harbor. Pretty soon a NAVY tug was pressing
the Moby Dick, so we interposed "Les Deux Amis" to prevent
boarding.
<p>
When the Moby Dick dropped anchor, which was still
some way off the berth, it seemed best to go on, try to get
closer, carry the action further. Inflatables of Greenpeace
were having difficulty crossing the floating boom surrounding
the berth, although 2 did manage in the end. No way our boat
could do that, so we motored along parallel to the boom,
heading inland, as that was where an opening must have been
left, as the Pacific Pintail was heading that way. We hadn't
been bothered much until this stage by the military. As we
approached close to crossing the path of the nuclear carrier,
a patrol boat came alongside. First of all he just pushed, to
push us off course, but was not able to. Unfortunately he
caught a rope off the deck, and was able to tug back on it. It
seemed that something got caught around the propellor just
then, so I had to cut the motor. That was about it. By this
time the Moby Dick was swarming with police. The action was
just about over. The nuclear ship drew alongside the berth,
hardly hindered at all.
<p>
After some hours being towed around the outer harbor, we were
towed back in to the berth we had started from, reports were
made. The day dawned. As I returned to the boat from the
police bus SkyHawk said to look : a Rainbow, a complete bow
arc in the west.
<p>
Now we are free! We went ashore to drink coffee and get warm.
The CRS police, 30 of them, remained guarding our boat until
the Pacific Pintail left port about 11.30 am.
We went to the barrel monument Greenpeace had set up, and
stuck up the signs representing the many Indigenous Tribes who
have suffered under the nuclear industry.
<p>
It was then we heard the land team had been arrested too. Norb
from the USA and Geert and Pol from Belgium had tried to
display a 20 meter long banner 'Stop nuclear terrorism' at the
entrance to the loading crane around 04.00. Although a legal
action, they were taken to the police office until departure
of the Pacific Pintail out of the Cherbourg harbor.
<p>
We saw the Pacific nuclear dustbin boat sail. The sun was
shining. The Moby Dick crew were released. Soon afterwards the
FOR MOTHER EARTH team had to leave. I was sorry we couln't
spend a little more time unwinding together. We just came
together for a few days - didn't know much about each other -
but knew each other enough. Oh well, back on the road to
Moscow, or in my case to get my broken boat back home to
Guernsey.
<p>
Greenpeace tracked the Pintail from Cherbourg and on into the
Atlantic. More countries denied her access to their waters en
route - Spain, Portugal, Chile, Argentina, South Africa.
She's still on the way, going to have a long voyage, and
precious few friendly ports on the way.
<p>
I guess we've got a little more work to do, till this nuke
death industry closes. It is on the way through.
<p>
<i>Thanks 'FOR MOTHER EARTH'<p>Jonathan Castle</i>

<address>
FOR MOTHER EARTH International, Gent, Belgium
</address><A HREF=/~fme/wae/waeidx.html>[INDEX]</A> <A HREF=wrep017.html>[NEXT]</A>

</body>
</html>

