<html>
<HEAD><TITLE>Walk Action Report 13 - Doel NPP</TITLE></HEAD>

<body>
<A HREF="/~fme/wae/waeidx.html"><IMG SRC  = "/~fme/images/walkhome.gif" ALT="Walk Across Europe Home Page"></A>

<H2>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE</H2>
<H2>Belgium, Doel - March 11 1995</H2>


<HR>
<H1>Five hundred people gather at nuclear power plant of Doel </H1>


<P>
<B>Doel, Saturday March 11th 1995 - As the Walk across Europe
arrived in the village of Doel, over 500 people gathered in a
demonstration for the closure of the NPP of Doel, near Antwerp
in Belgium. Besides seventy anti-nuke walkers, there was a
remarkable presence of members of local groups opposing a rad-
waste dump in their region, and of members of the Belgium Green
Party.
</B><P>

The Doel NPP counts 4 of the seven reactors in Belgium. Three
others are located in Tihange NPP, near Namur.
<P>
The demonstration was organised by FOR MOTHER EARTH, JNM,
Milieuaktiekamp and the NIRAS-working group. The NIRAS working
group gathers grass-root activists from several environmental
NGO's in an effort to empower an emerging new anti-nuclear
network.
<P>
NIRAS is the name of the Belgian governmental department
responsable to manage nuclear waste. Last year NIRAS publicized
its plan to build an underground bunker to store low-level rad-
waste. They are investigating 98 different spots in 47 different
Belgian municipalities. At the end NIRAS will choose one site.
As a result a massive local grass-roots movement emerged to
protest against rad-waste in their back-yard.
<P>
The NIRAS-working group's first main purposes is to create
stronger cooperation and solidarity amongst all those local
groups opposing the bunker. The second main purpose is to
denounce further production of rad-waste through closure of
Belgian two NPP.
<P>
The demonstrators denounced the proposed short-sighted solution
of the underground bunker. They demand above-ground storage which
can be controlled at all times. The demonstrators however
highlighted the need of a broad public debate around nuclear
power. Belgium produces nearly 60% of its electricity with
nuclear power. The nearly 70 cross-continntal walkers stressed
the need to stop the production of rad-waste at the very first
step of the nuclear chain, namely uranium mining. For every 500
grams of uranium, one ton of radio-active tailings are left
behind. It are mostly Indigenous People's environment and their
health which suffers from uranium mining, as 70 to 80% of all
uranium mining is taking place on their lands.
<P>
	    Walk in the Netherlands
<P>
The walkers are now on their way through the Netherlands, where
a demonstration is planned at the NPP of Dodewaard on Saturday
March 18th.
<HR>
<address>For more information on the Dutch part,
please contact FOR MOTHER EARTH NETHERLANDS :
Benno Linssen +31-80-223434</address>

