<HEAD><TITLE>The Walk in the Netherlands </TITLE></HEAD>

<body>
<A HREF="/~fme/wae/waeidx.html"><IMG SRC="/~fme/images/walkhome.gif" ALT="Walk Across Europe Home Page"></A> <A HREF="/~walk/contacta.html"><IMG SRC  = "/~walk/images/contacta.gif" ALT="Contact Addresses"></A> <A HREF=wrep013.html><IMG SRC = "arrwleft.gif"></A><A HREF="wrepovv.html"><IMG SRC  = "actreprt.gif"  ALT="Action Report" ></A><A HREF=wrep015.html><IMG SRC = "arrwriht.gif"></A>

<H2>for immediate release</H2>
<H2>Utrecht NL, March 20, 1995 </H2>
<hr>

<h1>THE WALK IN HOLLAND</h1>

<i>(Report from 'Omslag', one of the Dutch organizations supporting
the Walk across Europe for a nuclear free world)</i><P>

<b>Last week the Walk went through Holland. We've been so busy, we
couldn't find the time to write messages. Now we know the reason
why there was so little news...</b>
<p>
Now it is monday and the walkers are in Germany. We're tired and
satisfied. All the work we did to prepare things was worthwile!
<p>
Our organization, 'Omslag, Workshop for sustainable development'
has supported the walk in Holland. We asked all our donators,
subscribers and sympathisers to do something: join the walk for
a few days, tell other people about it, distribute posters,
organize actions and sign the international petition for a
nuclear-free world. When the walkers were in Holland, we could
give them 1832 signed petitions.
<p>
In februari, before the walk arrived, there were five meetings
in different cities, where people watched the video-tape about
the Walk across America (1992) and there was a lecture about
nuclear energy, nuclear weapons, the indigeous people and the
Non Proliferation Treaty.
<p>
It was amazing to see how many people wanted to help. Nature-
food-shops gave 'food-donations' and one shopkeeper offered his
clients 'Walk-miles'. That's something like 'Air-Miles', whith a
little difference: people paid a donation to support the walk.
Others offered a foot-massage for the walkers, organized
sleeping places, a tea-concert and so on.
<p>
Last tuesday (march 14) we were really nervous. We prepared
everything as well as we could, now it was going to happen!
Twentyfive people went to the Dutch-Belgium border to meet the
walkers there. The moment when both groups met was great!
Together we walked to Tilburg, where seventy people arrived.
During last week the walk grew every day.
<p>
In Goirle the walkers were welcomed by a local peace-group. They
served coffee and gave the walkers a peace-message. Goirle has a
partner-town near Moscow (Krasnagorsk) and they asked the
walkers to bring the peace-message to the Krasnagorsk people.
<p>
After a party and sleeping in Tilburg the Walk went to Liempde
on Wednesday (march 15). It was a nice day, walking through the
nature-area 'Kampina'. In the afternoon the walkers were
welcomed by people from Boxtel. There was a tea-concert given by
'Strijk en Zet' and people from the famous environmental-centre
'The Small Earth' served coffee and herb-tea.
<p>
Thursday (march 16) we were not joining the walk. We had to do
some other work.
<p>
Friday-morning (march 17) we got a telefone-call. Krista told
the walkers had decided to have an extra action, that was not
scheduled. It would start at eleven o clock. Could we help to
inform the press...?
<p>
The action was on the military air-base Volkel, the only place
in Holland where nuclear weapons are stored. The idea was, to
enter the air-base to have a pick-nick there. We cant't tell
much about it, because we were not there, we were at home near
the telephone, calling all newspapers and radiostations we knew.
An action-report will be distributed later...
<p>
Friday-evening we were in Nijmegen. There was a meeting to talk
about the action next day. Many people were there and everybody
was very interested.
<p>
Saturday (march 18) it was the day of the great event: we were
gonna close the nuclear power plant Dodewaard!
<p>
In the morning all walkers and many others gathered on the
'Square 1944' in Nijmegen. Although the weather had been
excellent untill now, this day started with rain and storm. But
in the afternoon, when the action took place, the sun had
returned and there was just enough wind to make the windmills
turning.
<p>
From the square it was a 16-kilometer walk to Dodewaard. There
were more than 150 people. Many of then had coloured faces and
masks. When we arrived, two totempoles were placed near the
entrance of the plant. Windmills were placed upon the totems. A
big banner 'Doodlopende weg' (Dead end street) was put between
the totems. The symbolic closure of Dodewaard was a fact.
A big spider-web was made of wool. Music, songs and drums
created a wonderful, peaceful atmosphere. The sun had returned
and everywhere you could see banners and signs, like 'fish in
the water, birds in the sky, uranium in the ground' and 'we have
only one earth, handle with care'.
<p>
Dirk Jan Dullemond, one of the walkers, made a speech. The
Dodewaard-NPP was built in 1969, but almost immediately after
the start it had to be closed temporarly, because it was not as
save as was told.
<p>
The NPP in Dodewaard is located on a small island in the river
Waal. It can only be reached via a long bridge. Until this
moment the action took place at the front-end of the bridge.
Seven policemen were standing there to make sure nobody went on
the bridge. But after the speech some people managed to pass
them. We saw activists running on the bridge, followed by
policeman. More and more activists followed. After some time
the bridge was in the hands of the activists and the police
decided to 'defend' the gate at the other side of the bridge.
This situation made it possible to negotiate: 'We want talk to
the director of the NPP before we are leaving the bridge'.
<p>
The negotiations took a lot of time: How many people in the
delegation? Are you really leaving after the talk? Is the press
allowed to join the delegation?
<p>
At the end three women were allowed to have a talk. When they
came back they told us, the director had been very nervous. In
his opinion there is a big difference between nuclear weapons
and nucleair power. 'I want peace too, but we have to defend our
freedom. Dodewaard is a very safe NPP' he said.
<p>
The delegation told him about the indegeous people, suffering
from uranium-mining. It was a new story for him, since he only
knows about statistics.
<p>
During the action one of us was at the Mother Earth-office in
Nijmegen calling the press. The activists in Dodewaard had a
portable phone (borrowed from Greenpeace), so it was possible to
inform the office every minute. This was very important!
Make sure there is a portable phone when there are actions!
 <p>
In the beginning the press seemed not very interested. But when
we could tell them 'we have closed the NPP now' they were more
interested. And after we had 'taken' the bridge, they came to
Dodewaard to see it. But the television didn't come. Why? 'There
was no violance, there has been no escalation'.
<p>
It is disappointing to see how difficult it is to make the media
interested when you want to have a non-violent action. In the
past there have been a lot of actions in Dodewaard with a lot of
police and a lot of fighting. Every television watcher knows
about it. But when there is a non-violent action, it is not
shown on television.
<p>
Today we sent a 'letter to the editor' to some important
newspapers in Holland. 'This way, the media are promoting
violence', we wrote.
<p>
There is a lot more to tell. We hope to read more stories from
others who joined the walk in Holland. And we are very
interested in new information from Germany, Russia and all the
other countries where the Walk will be. Omslag will keep the
readers of our magazine 'ZOZ' as informed as possible. So please
keep us informed!
<p>
<i>Marta Resink, Dick Verheul</i>
<hr>
Omslag - Workshop for Sustainable Development<br>
P.O.-box 163 - 5270 AD Sint-Michielsgestel - The Netherlands
Phone +31 (0)4194-1622 / +31(0)30-730100 - E-mail <A HREF="mailto:omslag@aps.nl">omslag@aps.nl</a>

<HR>

<address>
FOR MOTHER EARTH International, Gent, Belgium
</address><A HREF=/~fme/wae/waeidx.html>[INDEX]</A> <A HREF=wrep015.html>[NEXT]</A>

</body>
</html>




