<html>
<HEAD><TITLE>Walk Action Report 15 - Dodewaard NPP </TITLE></HEAD>

<body>
<A HREF="/~fme/wae/waeidx.html"><IMG SRC="/~fme/images/walkhome.gif" ALT="Walk Across Europe Home Page"></A> <A HREF="/~walk/contacta.html"><IMG SRC  = "contacta.gif" ALT="Contact Addresses"></A>

<H2>for immediate release</H2>
<H2>Nijmegen, March 18, 1995</H2>

<HR>
<H1>Nuclear power plant of Dodewaard blocked</h1>
<h1>Delegation received by director </H1>

Last Saturday March 18th approx. 110 participants of the FOR
MOTHER EARTH Walk across Europe for a Nuclear-Free World were
joined by another 100 activists for a day of action at the NPP
of Dodewaard in the Netherlands.
<p>
The walkers left the city of Nijmegen in the morning for a
16km hike to the power-plant. The walkers were carrying about
70 signs with names of Indigenous People who are affected by
uranium mining and/or nuclear testing. The action at the NPP
of Dodewaard was organized by the FOR MOTHER EARTH
Netherlands. According to FOR MOTHER EARTH 70 to 80% of all
uranium is mined on Indigenous People's land. The Netherlands
is importing its uranium from the Americas, Africa and
Australia. For every 500 grams of uranium, a ton of radio-
active waste is left behind, which is creating environmental
and health damage.
<p>
Not the rain, hail or wind could stop walkers from arriving at
the NPP in the early afternoon. At their arrival a non-violent
blockade was started with a banner saying 'Dead end road' and
with two wooden peace-poles being erected at both sides of the
only entrance. Between the poles a woolen web was weaved while
the protestors were singing songs and making music. When
activists started to tresspass on the bridge leading to the
NPP policemen used force in an attempt to stop them. With the
activists displaying non-violent behavior, the police however
could not stop them, and soon about sixty activists were
occupying the bridge. After one and a half hour of
negotiations with the police, it was agreed that a delegation
of three people would have a dialogue with the director of
Dodewaard NPP.
<p>
Laura Johnson (USA), Grace O'Sullivan (Ireland) and Alina
Pakhirko (Belarus) represented the walkers. The delegation
stressed the relation-ship of the Dodewaard NPP with the
contamination of the Irish sea (Dodewaard spent fuel being
reprocessed in Sellafield), the risk of an accident and the
human and environmental cost of the mining of uranium and the
depositing of radioactive waste on Indigenous People's land.
<p>
Dodewaard is a quite small reactor (54MW) and was the first
NPP to be built in the Netherlands. Originally the plant was
to be shut in 1995, but closure is currently being delayed
until 2004, and it is expected that it will even be delayed
until 2007.
<p>
The Walk across Europe entered into Germany on Sunday March
19th on its way to the Czech Republic, Austria, Slovakia,
Ukraine, Belarus to end in Moscow on October 12th 1995.
October 12th is the International Day of Solidarity with
Indigenous People.
<p>
			     -end-
<P>
<HR>
For more information, registrations and financial support:

<address>
FOR MOTHER EARTH International, Gent, Belgium
</address><A HREF=/~fme/wae/waeidx.html>[INDEX]</A> <A HREF=wrep016.html>[NEXT]</A>

</body>
</html>




