<HEAD><TITLE> Statement for media, jan.12, 1995   </TITLE></HEAD>

<body>
<A HREF="/~fme/wae/waeidx.html"><IMG SRC  = "/~fme/images/walkhome.gif" ALT="Walk Across Europe
Home Page"></A> 
<IMG SRC ="/~fme/images/arrwleft.gif"></A><A HREF="wrepovv.html">
<IMG SRC  = "/~fme/images/actreprt.gif" ALT="Action Report" ></A>
<A HREF=wrep002.html><IMG SRC = "/~fme/images/arrwriht.gif"></A>

<H2>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE</H2>
<H2> Statement for media, (USA) Jan.12, 1995  </H2>

<HR>
<H1> Statement for media, jan.12, 1995 </H1>

<P>
<B>Contact: Mark D. Stansbery, (614)252-9255
January 10, 1995
</B><P>
[Community Organizing Center and For Mother Earth, North America
will participate in the "No Nukes, No Way!" Nukes have no
Borders! Press Conference in Columbus, Ohio (USA)]
<P>
Today, January 12, 1995, The Walk across Europe for a Nuclear-
Free World steps off toward a nuclear free world.  An
international effort has brought about a profound civilian plea
for a just peace.  The organizers from more than ten countries
and local activists call on world leaders to 1) bring about a
Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty and extend the Nuclear
NonProliferation Treaty in 1995; 2) transform the International
Atomic Energy Agency into an International Energy Agency that
controls the nuclear industry and promotes alternative energy
technologies; and 3) redeploy the international human and social
resources toward nonviolent conflict, renewable and sustainable
energy source technology, and nongovernment expertise.
<P>
The WALK represents an intentional community that chooses direct
actions such as walking with humility, talking together
prophetically, and visiting nuclear waste sites in order to
demonstrate commitment to a nuclear-free world.  The organizers
call the WALK project a nine-month action that will demonstrate
alternative forms of technology and sociology.
<P>
Today, we walk together calling for the end of the nuclear
industry as it has been constituted for the past 50 years.  This
year, 1995, also is the 50th anniversary of the United Nations;
therefore, the two reformations of the nuclear industry and of
the United Nations Network are inalienably related.   As it is
now, the weapons of mass destruction and the scores of polluted
communities will be the only legacy of the nuclear age.  In
several situations, hypocrisy or malignant neglect, outright
malice of intent, could characterize the nuclear industry; so why
should not anyone of sound mind question the promises of the very
same nuclear industry.
<P>
The residents of Ohio and several other states who were either
tricked, coerced, or maligned into multistate compacts for
radiological waste disposal host status at the bequest of the
nuclear generators face some serious decisions in these coming
months and years.  In the past two years, much attention has been
upon the nuclear industry and governmental resolution to the 1985
U.S. Congress Radwaste compact agreements.  However, public
consent is still not clear nor assured.
<P>
Decisions made with wide participation can not be hurried or
careless.  When the U.S. Congress passed the 1985 Radwaste
compact agreement, the Ohio General Assembly passed supportive
legislation without much thought on the consequences of which the
Radwaste compact poses.  Who was making decisions then, are they
still in the General Assembly. If so, can they tell us of the
debate that took place prior to their vote?
<P>
Can the federally unfunded mandates argument be made here that
the Radwaste compact agreement is a Federal mandate not
adequately funded; I don't know, possibly you might ask the
accessible Governor George Voinoich.  Being one of the national
spokespersons for that movement, Governor Voinoich, it would
seem, accepts this federally unfunded mandate.
<P>
The Senator Suhadolnik (R-Parma) introduced Senate Bill 358 at
the end of last Session and will introduce the same legislation
this January. The Bill enables the formation of a Radwaste
Development Authority that would initiate the search process for
three possible host sites in Ohio to geopolitically characterize
their pontential to house nuclear waste from six states
(Minnesota, Iowa, Missouri, Wisconsin, Indiana, and Ohio).
However, the potential Radwaste sources continue to grow as the
Midwest Compact already was approached by the Central States
Compact in order to negotiate agreement on acceptance of nuclear
waste from another six states.	Moreover, the Department of
Energy/Defense has initiated efforts to reclassify its waste
which can only indicate that the Radwaste Compact source
potential grows.
<P>
The nuclear industry knows that quick solutions do not create
large public anger, since the public will not know the
consequences of these decisions for years to come.  Since the
beginning of the nuclear age, the governmental organizations
worldwide and the nuclear industry have coordinated large scale
fraud and coverup.   As evidenced by the Fernald, Mound, and
Piketon nuclear weapons factories in Ohio, residents and workers
should not expect forthcoming information nor remediation without
strong public outcry from any proposed nuclear waste dispository.
<P>
Today, we might be only a whisper; but our words stretch the
globe.	Throughout the past two years that the Radwaste public
hearings were conducted, community organizers and organizational
leaders have faced a potential Goliath. However as David was able
to neutralize Goliath, the residents of Ohio will tie the Nuclear
Goliath's sandals. How ever the decision procedes, I know this
one fact that decades from now, no one will be able proclaim that
there was no opposition.
<P>
Without full financial record disclosure of elected officials and
of nuclear industrial operatives who choose to exert political
clout, can the public discussions and subsequent policy decisions
be made? I think not!  Furthermore, should not the local
residents of a proposed host community have the right to accept
or reject an industrial site?  The present legislation does not
allow electoral decisions by proposed host communities.
<P>
In conclusion, scientific progress must benefit the social
imperatives of a society, and society depends on technological
progress to sustain motion toward a just future.  However, the
Radwaste compact agreement does not create sociological benefit
nor represent technological progress.  The proposed Radwaste
Development Authority Commission would better serve the residents
of Ohio by searching for alternative energy sources that could
sustain an economic and environmental dynamic society.
<P>
Thank you for your time and consideration in attending the "NO
Nukes, No Way" Nukes know no boundaries! press conference.  This
consortium will conduct weekly media events during the Wednesday
hearings of January and February in the Ohio General Assembly and
begin to mobilize effort to recind the U.S. Congress 1985
Radwaste Compact agreement.
<P>
Please do not hesitate to ask the tough questions of the policy
makers.
<P>
*************************end*************************************
<P>
This statement will be read with some alterations at the "No
Nukes, No Way" press confernce where Greenpeace, community and
worker organization, and Native American representatives will
participate.   Peace
<P>
<address>Mark D. Stansbery  (walk@igc.apc.org)</address>

<P>
<HR>
For more information, registrations and financial support:

<address>

FOR MOTHER EARTH International, Gent, Belgium
</address><A HREF=/~fme/waeidx.html>[INDEX]</A> <A HREF=wrep002.html>[NEXT]</A>
</body>
</html>
