<html>
<HEAD><TITLE>The Walk in Slovakia - report </TITLE></HEAD>

<body>
<A HREF="/~fme/wae/waeidx.html"><IMG SRC="/~fme/images/walkhome.gif" ALT="Walk Across Europe Home Page"></A>

<h1>Report Walk in Slovakia</h1>


<h2>Friday 26th of May: Bratislava (1st day in Slovakia)</h2>
Again, we had some problems to get all people on the walk over
the next border. This time the people of Belarussia and Turkey
were not allowed to get into Slovakia. The border guards refused
to allow them to pass, claiming the paper-work was not correct.
A TV news crew showed up and the gaurds attempted to keep them
and us seperate. After a stand-off it was agreed to allow every-
one to cross if we pay a large sum of money AND if we did not
talk to the reporters. And that's what we did ...<p>

It was obvious that the news crew made them nervous, things would
have certainly  been different had they not been there. The event
lasted more than two hours.<p>

The local organizers from Slovakia were already waiting for us.
The sleeping place was a park a little bit outside Bratislava.
It was a long walking-day, no time to see the town. 
The local organizers decided that there would not be a restday
in Bratislava. Later the evening we had a meeting with the local
organizers about the route, the organisation of the walk in
Slovakia, and a lesson on 'how to behave in the east'.     <p>

<h2>Saturday 27th of May: Sener</h2>
Lately these days, the walk is often very much spread out during
walking. We slept at a camping place with a lake. We had to watch
out for thievs and put the tents near to each other. Rampenplan
made a very nice dinner.<p>

<h2>Sunday 28th of May: outskirt of Trnava</h2>
We had a meeting about an action in Bohunice NPP. There were
quite big differences between the ideas of local organisers and
the ideas of people on the walk. The idea of direct action was
not attractive for the local organisers.<p>

<h2>Monday 29th of May: Malzenice</h2>
Risa (the local organiser) gave us the feeling that it is quite
dangerous here, he even warns us not to walk around in the
village and go to the pub as we are very nearby the Nuclear Power
Plant (NPP) and that means that people don't like us. We had a
long (tiring) meeting about actions, and finally reached
consensus; we won't do a direct action.<p>

<h2>Tuesday 30th of May: Action in NPP Bohunice</h2>
Some kilometers outside the NPP, a bus was waiting for us. Half
of the group went with banners to the NPP. Another group went to
the information center of the NPP. The people working there 
showed us a model of the NPP, and spoke about the dangers, they
compared Bohunice with Tsjernobyl ... They showed a video, and
there was again a discussion with local speakers. We gave our
message and kept the last word.<p>

<h2>Fiday 2nd of June:Levice</h2>
Finally a rest-day, washing clothes ... The entire garden is
covered with wash lines.
Later in the evening we had a circle about Mohovce action. We
decide to go there by bus, then walk to the plant. Again problems
between organizers and walk. But we decided not to do a direct
action.<p>

<h2>Saturday 3rd of June: Action NPP Mohovce</h2>
Mohovce is a NPP that is built but is still not on line. Slovakia
needs more money, and it's likely that Russia is going to invest
in Mohovce NPP, probably a big part of the energy will also go
to Russia ...<br>
Around 9am we walk with banners to the main square, then to the
bus station, but no bus showed up. So Charlie, the gear bus of
the walk, brings us in two trips 8KM away where the police stop
us. There is some press, NPP people. We stop but go on to the
main gate. People are singing and dancing, some "die"
symbollically.<p>
Others climb onto a monument and do a "see,hear,say nothing"
symbol. TV arrives. The local org.'s say they [the press] don't
like us but, 2 day's later the reports were OK. 3 people entered
to give our message and signatures.<br>
There were also some Dutch people behaving as thick skinned
elephants, spraying graffiti on walls. Unfortunately 'No Mohovce'
was spelled wrong ... and local organisers were furious ...<p>

<h2>Monday 5 June: Banska Stavinica</h2>
We walked through the forest,up into the hills. much rain and fog
We were to sleep next to a lake,but went on, as the next day was
to be a long one. The town is a nice one with old castles and
churches. The local org. found an unfinished kinder-garden to
sleep in. After dinner,music and dance with Gypsy's.<p>

<h2>Tuesday 6 June: Sliac</h2>
Charlie has a minor problem in the morning but is repaired before
lunch.Nice walk thru a valley. Meeting after dinner to make 6
groups with translators who will go to local schools the next
day.Later we had a second meeting with local environmental groups.<p>

<h2>Wednesday 7 June: Detva</h2>
A wonderful breakfast served by local people. Morning circle was 
crowded with school children.We go to the school classes. In my
group we explained things on the black-board, showed them
maps,telled our story...We leave at 10, walk thru Zvolen.
Sleeping-place with real beds!  <p>
   
<h2>Thursday 8 June: Dubakova</h2>
We leave Detva and the road for a nice footpath over some hills.
First blister stop to lunch is uphill but with a beautiful
view.The group splits into two,road walkers and mountain
climbers.Some of the latter became lost and arrive very late in
the evening. 3 walkers are still missing.<p>
   
<h2>Friday 9 June: Hnusta</h2>
The lost walkers arrive early in the morning! They slept in a
forest and found our arrows - the arrows we use to mark the route
each day - again in the morning. 
We had an evaluation meeting about Mohovce. The local organisers
are still not happy with it, but after the last news reports -
which were defenitely not negative - the atmosphere became much
better.<p>
      
<h2>Saturday 10 June: Sirk</h2>
'Evening speak-out' about group process. A speak-out is a circle
were each person speaks and everybody else listens without
commenting. So instead of a speak-out, perhaps a better name
would be 'a listen-in'!        <p>
   
<h2>Sunday 11 June: Stitnik</h2>
Terrible thunderstorm at night. We sang and danced in the rain 
'till our feet were 15 cent. under water. Charlie is crowded at
night.                          <p>
  
<h2>Monday 12 June: Vrasnahonske-Podhradie</h2>
Still more rain. We slept in little cottages near a castle. The
people here speak Hungarin.                    <p>
 
<h2>Monday, tuesday and wednesday 12, 13&14 June</h2>
Walking in the rain and rest-days in the rain.       <p>


<h2>Thursday 15 June: Kosice</h2>
We had a long day with a demonstration in the town, mostly just
marching through the town with banners, passing out flyers ETC.
the people for the most part tried to ignore us as is usual in
these eastern countries. But when one person takes a flyer or
talks to us then there will be 10 behind them who will also take
a flyer or listen to us.         <p>

<h2>17th and 18th of June</h2>
We're reaching the border of Ukraine. These days there is not so
much political activities anymore. We are walking and surviving.
Some more Ukrainian people arrive to the walk. They offered us
to do psychological tests to compare eastern and western thinking
...                           <p>
In the night, people on the walk are having nightmares about
tomorrow: crossing another border, the police are and probably
will be a constant companion throughout Ukraine.<p>

<h2>19th of June</h2>
For the first time in the 'small' history of this walk, we do NOT
have any difficulties to cross another border. People without
visa can go in at no charge! The local evironmental organisations
are allready waiting for us at the Ukraine side of the border.
They wellcome us with traditional bread and other food. More
Belarussians and Ukraine people join us. We're now more than 70
walkers ... and in front of us a number of police cars.<p>

<HR>
For more information, registrations and financial support:

<address>
FOR MOTHER EARTH International, Gent, Belgium
</address><A HREF=/~fme/wae/waeidx.html>[INDEX]</A> <A HREF=wrep023.html>[NEXT]</A>

</body>
</html>

