<html>
<HEAD><TITLE>Walk Across Europe Action Report   </TITLE></HEAD>

<body>
<A HREF="/~fme/wae/waeidx.html"><IMG SRC="/~fme/images/walkhome.gif" ALT="Walk Across Europe Home Page"></A>
<A HREF="/~fme/wae/reports/wrepovv.html"><IMG SRC  = "/~fme/images/actreprt.gif"  ALT="Action Report" ></A>
<p>

<plaintext>
We did it!!!! We finally arrived on the Red Square,
one day later then scheduled, due to arrests
yesterday in Moscow (see release October 12th).


FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE

Walkers finally end 5500 km anti-nuclear wal
               on Red Square in Mosco

>>> PHOTOGRAPHS AND HI-8 VIDEO FOOTAGE AVAILABLE
E-mail : office@motherearth.knooppunt.be
                          
           Campaign continued with boycot
           and Memorial walk Chernobyl 10+

Moscow October 13th 1995 - After the release of the
last three FOR MOTHER EARTH peacewalkers who wer
arrested yesterday, the international anti-nuke
walkers could finally end their monumental 5.500 km
and nine month journey  on the Red Square in
Moscow. The walkers were overjoyed, and put out
their worn off shoes to dance, before the polic
asked them to leave the Red Square.

An average of 60 walkers from more then 20
different countries have don non-violent actions
at numerous nuclear facilities since they lef
Brussels last January 12th. They walked an average
of 25 km/day in an effort to halt nuclear testing,
outlaw nuclear weapons, phase out nuclear energy
and promote renewable energy and energy savings
technologies. 

The walkers had originally planned to end the walk
yesterday, on the International Day of Solidarit
with Indigenous People. FOR MOTHER EARTH has bee
campaigning since 1991 to denounce the nuclea
industry using lands of indigenous people for
uranium mining, nuclear testing and disposal of
rad-waste. 

Yesterday the Moscow police however put a brutal
halt to the end of the walk by arresting 1
peacewalkers. Today the last three walkers were
finally also set free without any charge.

The previous months the 'Walk across Europe for a
Nuclear-Free World' went through Chernobyl
contaminated areas in Ukraine and Belarus. The
also had actions at the French embassies in Kiev,
Minsk and Moscow to denounce the renewal of nuclear
testing in Polynesia. 

Today the walkers return home where they will cal
consumers to boycott French products and services. 

Next year, for the tenth anniversary of Chernobyl,
FOR MOTHER EARTH plans to organise a memorial wal
to this nuclear power plant. FOR MOTHER EARTH wil
also call other organisations to organise actions
at nuclear power plants worldwide.

                        -end
NOTE
Television footage      Reuters and WT
Photo's                 Reuters and Itar-Tass


