<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>PACHAWO
GENERAL INFORMATION (level 2)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER><H1>PACHAWO</H1>
<P><IMG SRC="rainban.gif">
<H3>European Action Camp for young people in World Shops<BR>
17 - 24 August 1996, Lichtaart - Belgium</H3></CENTER>
<IMG SRC="rainban.gif">
<P>
<EM>"Pachawo" is the Shona word (the main language in Zimbabwe) for "togetherness"(*). And thats exactly the idea we want to bring forward in our European camp for young volunteers in World Shops.</EM>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=-2>(*) to-geth-er-ness / n (U)  a feeling of being united with other people in a friendly relationship</FONT>
<P>
<H5>Different...</H5><BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>Since the creation of the European Union, Europe pretends to be united. But behind this administrative and economic construction, there remain a lot of different countries with different cultures...
In almost every country of Europe there are organizations engaging in Fair Trade : buying products, like coffee, cocoa, sugar, handicrafts etc., from small producer groups in Third World countries at a fair price, and selling them in World Shops. In the World Shops thousands of volunteers are working every day to make this Fair Trade work....
But every Fair Trade organization or World Shop organization is structured in a different way, functions in a different way...</FONT>
<P>
<H5>... but the same commitment</H5><BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>Differences are there to be explored, they incite to get to know each other. The commitment in any case is the same. No matter how World Shops in your country are organized, the vision behind all of them is our awareness that there is ONE world and it has to become a fairer world. As a World Shop volunteer you disagree with the present North-South relations, you see that the only motivation behind world trade is to pile up more money in the North, while the small farmer in the South doesnt get a fair share...</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=-1>Well, we thought it was time to bring all young people (16 to 23 year olds) working as a volunteer in a World Shop somewhere in Europe together on one camp.</FONT>
<P>
Lets explore our togetherness... PACHAWO !!!

<P>

<H5>The camp in action!</H5>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=-1>All together there will be more than 300 young people attending the camp. Coming from almost every World Shop organization in Europe.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=-1>Well be together for 8 days. How can we make this being together and our "togetherness" really meaningful? First of all by forming several small groups: your so-called home-base. In these small groups of 14 people, there will be plenty of time to talk, to exchange views and to get to know each other.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=-1>The whole day long there will be various workshops. This is where you mix with other home-bases so that you finally end up meeting everybody. You can pick your own workshops to participate in. In fact, by selecting workshops, youll make your own camp. There be many different workshops: from very creative (dancing, music, inventing things with recycled material, painting...) to deeply serious (discussions, assemblies,...). </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=-1>How serious ? First there will be some workshops about the World Shops and their organization in every country. The place and number of young people in your organization, youth-activities, ... What it means to be a volunteer in a World Shop in your country?
Secondly, we try to get a better view of each country and culture... Thirdly, we will not limit ourselves to Europe of course, but spend a good deal of time to learn about countries in the South through dancing, music, discussions, ... And as everything is linked with everything, well cant leave out topics like environment, refugees, racism etc.</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=-1>In between there will be plenty of time for sports, amusement and fun !</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=-1>And since we all share the same commitment in World Shops, we will demonstrate the strength of our togetherness in a spectacular action in Brussels at the end of the camp. 
With the 300 of us we will show the public and politicians that we are serious in our commitment and our longing for a fairer world. We will have the whole camp to carefully plan this action!</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=-1>So, this will be a camp with lots of things to do, new people to meet, but also ...
with plenty of room for your own creative participation: we want to be together in a group where everybody is equal and has the same rights and responsibilities. Therefore there will be a daily platform where you can have your say about the organization of the camp or whatever you want to bring about! We want to value the participation and contribution of every single participant at the camp. </FONT>
<P>
<IMG SRC="yl_bds.gif">
<STRONG>If you are:<BR>
- between 16 (°1980) and 23 (°1973) years old<BR>
- working as a volunteer in a World Shop in a European country<BR>
- able to communicate in English,<BR>
<BR>
you are very welcome (in fact "we expect you ...") to come to our PACHAWO-camp in August!!!</STRONG>
<P>
